Rating: 4
Stunning! My mother always made custards for desert at Christmas and Thanksgiving. For another idea - as I was growing up, being Scandinavian we often had simple beef broth served before a big meal and in it would be an almond "dumpling" really a custard because there was no flour in it, floating at the top. I have looked for years for a recipe that would fit the bill and this is exactly what I remember!

Rating: 4
This is great. I and all of my guests and family who have tried this love it. I very highly recommend using real almonds - tastes next to nothing like the extract and (in our opinions) produces a far superior taste and custard. I roast them on a sheet in the oven at 350 or so until browned (happens fast), cool a little, grind well (to a little coarser that a sugar- or sand-like consistency, takes a few seconds) in the food processor, and strain the custard milk in a strainer lined with a double layer of cheese cloth. This is virtually no work, does not take long at all, and (again, I find) it is definitely worth it.

Rating: 4
I love a twist on simple egg custard and this is wonderful! Because I had a LOT of cream on hand, I used heavy cream instead of half & half. Also, it was very late at night and rather than go through the straining of the almonds (which I did have on hand), I opted for the extract. It did take about 20 minutes longer to cook, but the end result was superb! Yes - this is a high fat dessert, but if you want low-fat, stay away from dairy! Non fat milk is not going to give you the results. Cardamom is also an acquired taste, I suppose, but it ranks high among my favorite spices. Its a wonderful "mystery" flavoring and I often search these pages specifically for the ingredient! Anyway - bravo for this recipe. I'll make it over and over again... with heavy cream, to be sure!

