Rating: 4
Fantastic!! I needed an easy dessert to go with an indian dinner. I make simple custards alot (which only use 2 cups whole milk and 3 whole eggs), and this one sounded great, but needed less milk. I used what I had on hand, and took the advice of using the almond extract (which saves a ton of time - and makes it a very quick and easy dessert, I think). I used 1 cup heavy cream, 1 cup 1% milk, 1/3 cup of sugar, 1 1/2 Tbsp honey, 1/2 tsp almond extract, and 1/2 tsp ground cardomom, 3 yolks, 2 whole eggs. I heated the milk/ cream in the microwave, (whisked the eggs and yolks while it was heating) stirred everything but the eggs into the hot liquid, then slowly whisked it into the eggs. The whole thing only took me about 10 minutes (including getting ingredients out and measuring). I cooked it a little longer (an hour I think) until a knife came out clean. We couldn't wait to try them, so we had them warm, and they were delicious. No need to make a day ahead. I will make this many times again! (The comment about the fat.. oh please, just eat one serving, and enjoy it!) Nice and simple finish, especially for an indian meal (Smothered Lamb from Madhur Jaffrey's Quick and Easy Indian Cooking) with so many complex flavors. Definitely a wonderful creamy ending to a meal. Even my 3 year old loved it!

